    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-03T20:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-03T20:00:00-05:00" n="1"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.001 Chiang Kai-shek/17: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-04T08:00:00+07:00"
                            >January 4, 1944—8 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 11:31 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>13. Chiang’s<note n="2" xml:id="d1fn2">Generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek, President
                        of the National Government of the Republic of China.</note> New Year radio
                    address to Chinese Army [and] people (Embassy’s 10, January 4<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d1fn3">Not printed.</note>) although made January 1, 1 a.m. was not
                    passed by censors until evening January 2. Mme. Chiang reportedly held up
                    release address due to disapproval English translation but foreign press
                    correspondents believed 48 hours delay must have been due other factors, finally
                    resolved after long discussion, such as (1) lavish praise United States,
                    President Roosevelt in contrast slight mention Great Britain, Churchill<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d1fn4">Winston S. Churchill, British Prime Minister.</note>
                    and (2) mention Chiang–Roosevelt conversation at Cairo regarding Japan.<note
                        n="5" xml:id="d1fn5">For documentation on the Cairo Conference, see <ref
                            target="frus1943CairoTehran">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, The Conferences at Cairo and
                            Tehran, 1943</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
